<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-638-739  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 638 739.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>ACM Transactions on Information Systems  April 1990 v8 n2p159(22).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Imprecise information and uncertainty in information systems.andO;(technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Morrissey, J.M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The function of information systems is to model, store,manipulate, and retrieve a wide variety of data.andP;  Sometimes someof the data is missing or imprecisely known or not applicable fora particular object.andP;  The way to handle this situation is to allowany attribute value to be a regular precise value, or a stringthat indicates the value is missing, or a string that indicatesthe attribute is not applicable, or an imprecise value.andO;Uncertainty is handled by retrieving two set of objects as a replyto every query.andP;  One set satisfies with complete certainty and oneset that possibly satisfies the query with varying degrees ofuncertainty.andP;  There are two methods, which are based oninformation theory, to estimate uncertainty.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Information Storage and RetrievalQuery ProcessingInformation TheoryData Base Management SystemsDesign.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>